export const chapterTranslations43to44: Record<number, string[]> = {
  43: [
    "That evening, Qinyan had endured a great deal of nonsense from Ji Liangxuan and Wu Dasha, and felt all the more oppressed in spirit. Fortunately they soon took their leave. He waited until the second watch, but seeing no sign of Baozhu or Sulan, he had no choice but to retire for the night.",
    "He lay sleepless through the night. At first light he sent a servant boy to summon the two of them.",
    "That morning, Sulan had already been called away by Wang Wenhui at an early hour. Presently Baozhu arrived. \"I missed you yesterday,\" said Baozhu. \"I did not return until the third watch, and no one thought to tell me. Your Wu'er only just mentioned it just now. I haven't seen you these two or three days — why haven't you come out to take the air? Today Duxiang has invited us to enjoy the apricot blossoms. Shall we all go together?\" \"Very well,\" said Qinyan. \"These past two days I have had a slight chill and felt rather weary. I too should like to go out for some air. Besides, my leave has run out, and I must soon think about returning to the city.\" \"A few more days can't hurt,\" said Baozhu. \"Once you go back, we shall be apart far more than we are together.\" \"There is something that has been troubling me of late,\" said Qinyan, \"and I am quite at a loss. I asked you and Xiangwan to come precisely so I might think of some plan with your help.\" \"Tell me what the trouble is,\" said Baozhu, \"though if you cannot think of a solution yourself, I am afraid I may fare no better.\" \"Yesterday my master's wife questioned me about the day I entered the Hua household — what Master Hua's young lord said to my shifu, and whether my shifu had ever received money from them. She also said that the household costs two thousand four hundred strings a month, and demanded that I pay her two hundred strings a month, saying she would not let me return to the city until this was settled. As I recall, I was sent in last year because of the Hua family's matter concerning Xi the Eleventh; after I entered I never even met my shifu, and I still don't know the full story. Now, out of nowhere, my master's wife is demanding two hundred strings from me a month — how am I ever to manage that? She also wants me to speak to Young Master Hua myself. She says that since my shifu died I have grown faithless. She claims the Hua household has never spent three or five thousand taels on me. Now she wants me to ask the young master to pay three thousand silver taels to buy out my indenture, and only then will she stop demanding monthly support from me. Otherwise, she says, she will depend on me for the rest of her life. As things stand, I have no engagements and cannot go out to entertain; the only income I have is the occasional festival gift from the household — how could I possibly save two hundred strings a month? You are a sensible person — is it possible to say such things to the young master? Is it not a dreadfully difficult matter? My master's wife simply does not understand how hard this is, and does nothing but demand money. Please think of some plan for me; I am utterly without ideas.\" Baozhu, hearing all this, felt the difficulty keenly. After pondering a while, she said: \"Two thousand four hundred strings a year comes to three thousand taels over three years. This 'support money' has no end to it. Young Master Hua has an uncertain temperament — one cannot rely on him. If you wished him to buy out your indenture, perhaps he might consent when in the right mood, but someone would need to approach him on your behalf. And there is another consideration: if he does buy out your indenture, you would in effect become his person, and could no longer act freely — you would likely spend the rest of your days in his household. This is something you must decide for yourself.\" \"I have thought of all that,\" said Qinyan, \"but even now, though I have not been formally released, I cannot act as a free person.\" \"If someone were to buy out your indenture,\" said Baozhu, \"what would you do afterward — remain outside, or would you be willing to enter the Hua household?\" \"I cannot decide that just yet,\" said Qinyan. \"Let me first be released, and then think about leaving the household.\" Baozhu laughed: \"Most people have only one way out of a contract. You seem to have two — mind you don't end up with seven causes for expulsion.\" Qinyan laughed as well.",
    "Just then Sulan walked in, and Qinyan and Baozhu invited her to sit. \"Where did you go so early?\" asked Qinyan. \"Lord Wang sent for me this morning,\" said Sulan. \"I thought it must be something urgent, but it turned out to be quite a trifling matter. I had a chat with Jiantan and Yong'an, and only just got home. I heard you had sent for me — what is it you need?\" Baozhu repeated everything that had just been discussed. Sulan clapped her hands and laughed: \"Just as I thought! Just as I predicted! I truly admire him. My view is that release from indenture is the right course — you should agree to it.\" \"Easy enough to say,\" said Qinyan. \"You settle the matter in a single breath. Where are the three thousand taels to come from? And could I possibly ask Young Master Hua for such a thing?\" \"Must it be exactly three thousand?\" said Sulan. \"What about two thousand — would that do?\" \"Now we're getting somewhere,\" said Baozhu. \"We invite you to help us think, and your first word is 'agree to the release,' your second is to slash the price — clearly you already have a plan. Does it not seem manageable?\" \"Someone else would still need to do the asking,\" said Qinyan. \"Whether it's three thousand or two thousand, I cannot say it to him myself.\" Baozhu asked Sulan: \"Even if we say two thousand, what is your brilliant scheme? Do enlighten us.\" \"This matter is one I had already thought through with someone more than ten days ago,\" said Sulan, \"and we had even discussed it once. But it was all uncertain, so I said nothing about it to anyone.\" \"And who is it you say you admire?\" asked Baozhu. \"One day I was chatting idly with Meixiang,\" said Sulan, \"and Yunong's name happened to come up. Meixiang said his master's wife—\" At this point Sulan glanced out the window and said: \"Can they hear us from over there?\" \"No, they cannot,\" said Qinyan. Sulan continued: \"Meixiang said his master's wife is as hard a taskmaster as his shifu was, and fears she will make Yunong support her for the rest of her life. Although Yunong does not perform anymore, he has still not been formally released. As for Yunong's money — it is not a small amount — but at this point he probably has little saved up. If four or five thousand strings could secure his release, we could pull something together among friends — a few of his close acquaintances might each contribute a share. I am speaking of you, the Wang brothers, Shoux­iang, Peixian, and the rest — surely none of them would refuse. If we could gather half, the other half would be easier.\" \"And what happens after the release?\" asked Baozhu. \"We did not get that far in our discussion,\" said Sulan. \"So long as he is released, this person belongs to himself. After that, naturally he may do as he pleases.\" \"If he remains in the Hua household, it is no different from not being released — he still cannot act freely,\" said Baozhu. \"Young Master Hua has not purchased him,\" said Sulan, \"and his shifu never drew up a deed of sale to the Hua household. How could he not be free? Is he to stay there his whole life?\" \"Speaking here is awkward after all,\" said Baozhu. \"Why don't we all go find Meixiang and discuss it? We can go to Duxiang's together and see the apricot blossoms — the ornamental peaches have opened splendidly too. I can't think why the season is so early this year; I remember the ornamental peaches blooming in the middle of the third month in past years. Duxiang is not hosting anyone today — there is nothing wrong with a few of us dropping in for a chat.\" Qinyan was very glad to go, and changed into fresh clothes, and ordered the carriage to be harnessed. As Sulan and Baozhu had come on foot, the two of them sent their attendants back to fetch their carriages, along with instructions about which garments to bring, all to be delivered to the Su family's Peixiang Hall.",
    "The two of them rode together in Qinyan's carriage to the place where Huifang was staying.",
    "It happened that Huifang was at home. The three of them entered, and found Huifang at the writing table looking over several album leaves. He rose with a smile to welcome them, saying: \"Today I have indeed received three uninvited guests.\" The three smiled, but did not sit down at once — they turned instead to look at the albums. Baozhu was the first to seize the painted one, and the other two clustered round to look with her. There were landscapes and flower studies, all rendered with great skill — Huifang had newly commissioned them from Master Qu Daoweng. On the last page was a painting of a beauty leaning on a balustrade in a mood of melancholy: fallen petals carpeted the ground below the railing, and a pair of swallows came flying through, as if evoking the lines: \"Fallen blossoms, and alone the one who stands; / A light spring rain, and swallows paired in flight.\" The image stirred in Qinyan's memory the riddle from long ago, and a sudden vague emotion passed over him. He read the quatrain inscribed below, and softly recited it to himself:",
    "\"Spring's colours fill the heart as swallows dart and fly, / Apricot blossoms in fine rain, yet my sleeves are dry.\n\n\"Alone I lean upon the rail and melancholy grows; / Where fragrant grasses stretch to heaven, you have yet to come.\"\n\nThey looked through the calligraphy album as well. Huifang invited the three to sit, and asked: \"Did you all arrive together by chance, or was this arranged?\" \"We came by arrangement,\" said Baozhu. \"Let us all go together to Duxiang's to see the apricot blossoms.\" \"Is there a banquet today?\" asked Huifang. \"No banquet,\" said Baozhu. \"Call it three uninvited guests — what is the harm?\" Huifang nodded and smiled his assent. Sulan's and Baozhu's clothes and carriages soon arrived; the two changed into fresh garments. Huifang went inside and changed as well, then asked: \"You came all this way together without any purpose? Simply to see the flowers?\" \"There is one matter to discuss,\" said Sulan. \"Let us talk of it at Yiyuan.\" \"Why not say a little now?\" said Huifang. \"It is still early — there is no need to hurry to Duxiang's.\" Sulan then briefly outlined the matter of Qinyan's master's wife demanding that Qinyan be released from his indenture. \"Indeed!\" said Huifang. \"I told you the other day, and you said it might not come to pass — yet here it is, just as I predicted. The matter is not so very difficult to arrange. The only fear is that a woman's word cannot be relied upon — she may agree today and change her mind tomorrow. Or she may name a figure and then keep raising it. And who is to go and speak with her?\" \"That is no great obstacle,\" said Sulan. \"We ourselves could go and speak with her.\" \"In that case, let us discuss it further at Yiyuan,\" said Huifang. And so they all boarded their carriages and drove directly to Yiyuan.",
    "Entering the garden, they passed beneath crimson peach boughs and emerald willows, beside green water and among blue hills. Crossing a red bridge and winding through ten layers of painted doors, they arrived at last at the East-Wind-Last-Night Tower. From above came the sound of clear singing and the tap of a clapperboard: someone was performing up there. The four of them halted to listen. It sounded like Duxiang's voice, singing a passage to the tune of \"Lan Hua Mei.\" They listened carefully:",
    "\"Say not that on the moon-bright Jasper Terrace we chanced to meet, / Or that atop the Mountain of Clustered Jade we claimed the highest seat. / I endure night after night while stars tilt and moon sinks, the cold upon me keen, / And day after day the copper vase and paper curtained bed hold winter's sting between — / Let me but taste that first faint thread of fragrant tidings, and be serene.\"\n\nNone of the four could place the text in any known score, yet the flute harmonies were delicately mournful and pleasant to the ear. Then they heard Ziyun laugh and say: \"That still won't do — let me come and play the flute instead.\" And then what seemed to be Cixian's voice singing:",
    "\"In this very pleasure-quarter, stars and moon dissolve in mist through the night, / I have heard every song and every flute that rides the river wind's flight. / It chimes with the curtain-ring's jade-clear striking, dingdong, dingdong bright, / Drawing me into the plum-blossom dream of parting-sorrow, parting-fright, / Until moon sets, stars wheel, and the bleak temple bell sounds the night's last rite.\"\n\nThe four were thoroughly absorbed in listening when the singing suddenly ceased. They heard Cixian say: \"Truly, sung aloud, the rhythm is quite beautiful.\" Then Ziyun: \"Why not transcribe the whole score with the gongche notation and have them learn it properly?\" The four, realising no more singing was coming, walked inside together. A page boy scrambled up the stairs to announce their arrival.",
    "Baozhu and the others climbed the staircase into the upper room. Cixian and Ziyun came forward with smiling faces; seeing Qinyan and Huifang among the visitors, they were all the more pleased, saying: \"We hardly expected you today.\" \"I brought them all,\" said Baozhu. And then, turning to Cixian: \"Shouxiang is unwell and could not come.\"",
    "This was Qinyan's first time ascending that tower. He saw that it curved and folded, rising in tier upon tier, spanning several dozen rooms, all wreathed in apricot blossoms. Some parts rose three storeys, others two; the passages branched in every direction, winding and opening unexpectedly, truly in the manner of a labyrinthine palace. Looking ahead, he could see the Peach Blossom Dell, set apart by a small hill.",
    "A clear stream ran between. The peach blossoms were in full bloom; the ornamental peaches were just half-unfurled; and together with the apricot blossoms beyond, the scene seemed as though clouds and rosy mists were rising together. Above the tower hung a plaque reading \"East-Wind-Last-Night Tower,\" with a long couplet below:",
    "\"One night of delicate, lingering rain — and lo, the swallows have flown in; / The curtain lifts on the east wind, where Northern Song and Southern Tang judged the music of the pleasure-quarters;\"\n\n\"Three parts of spring's allure — ask whether the apricot blossoms have yet opened; / Through latticed windows of carved jade, red castanets and ivory raps choose the songs of the singing-rooms.\"\n\nCixian and Ziyun observed that the four visitors were unusually well turned out that day — some resplendent, some elegant, as though each had taken pains to outshine the others. All four still wore their short fur outer jackets: Qinyan's was of dark fox-ear velvet, Baozhu's of dark fox with raked-claw pattern, Huifang's of cloud-fox with raked-claw pattern, and Sulan's of cloud-fox cut in domino-block points. Seen together, they were like coral trees and jade branches intertwined, like rare orchids and spirit-flowers vying in colour, so that the thousand red apricot boughs outside the tower could not match the four jade figures within. Even Cixian and Ziyun, accustomed as they were to such company, could not help glancing at them again and again. \"There are no elaborate dishes today — only a modest table,\" said Ziyun. \"If you are hungry, do begin.\" \"I confess I am rather hungry,\" said Huifang. Ziyun called for several confections to be brought first, and presently a few courses were set out, and they ate and drank lightly together. \"What was the piece you were just performing?\" asked Baozhu. \"The rhythm seemed quite familiar, but the words I did not recognise.\"",
    "\"A close friend of mine from years ago,\" said Cixian, \"composed a twenty-act drama score called Dream of the Plum Blossoms. The other day I found it at the bottom of a book-chest, and using the Nine-Palace Notation, I worked out the gongche for his lyric modes — it came out quite well in pitch. But I have only notated this one act, 'Entering the Dream'; whether the rest can be sung, I cannot say. Tomorrow I shall consult the musicians in your troupe and see if the whole can be scored.\" \"What a shame,\" said Huifang. \"I thought the text very fine. You had better score it yourself. If you give it to our musicians, they will smear and alter it until it conforms to their own mouths — cutting here, adding there, corrupting it past all sense. Unless one could ask Master Qu to advise.\" \"He has little interest in musical theory,\" said Cixian. \"Beyond playing the qin, nothing else engages him. If you speak to him of it, he simply says that since the Three Dynasties music has perished, and that is why the Book of Music was absorbed into the Rites.\" All four laughed. \"I have obtained some dried river scallops today,\" said Ziyun. \"Dried ones, of course — they make a finer broth than common dried seafood, though not equal to fresh.\" \"I have heard,\" said Qinyan, \"that fresh lychees paired with fresh river scallops have a flavour unlike anything else in the world. Dried lychees lose all their charm and are no better than longans. What can dried river scallops be like?\" Huifang suddenly fell into a deep reverie, silent and bowed in thought. Ziyun was rather surprised — Huifang was habitually lively and witty, so this sudden gravity was unexpected. \"Does Meixiang have something on his mind?\" asked Cixian. \"No,\" said Huifang. \"You were quite merry just now,\" said Ziyun. \"What has come over you?\" Baozhu and the others also noticed that Huifang seemed ill at ease. Huifang said nothing for a while, then spoke: \"How many days can a flower bloom?\" \"Seventy years,\" rejoined Cixian. \"How can that be?\" \"A person lives, by our reckoning, seventy years, and blooms a year for every year alive.\" \"This year's flowers are not last year's flowers.\" \"From last year's flowers come this year's flowers.\" \"Can this year's flowers last until next year?\" \"That depends on those who tend them.\" \"You have all suddenly taken up Chan riddles,\" said Sulan. \"In my view,\" said Qinyan, \"it would be better if flowers never bloomed at all.\" \"Why? I say it would be better if they never fell,\" said Baozhu. \"A flower that cannot fall is a flower that cannot bloom,\" said Huifang. \"Listen to what Yunong just said — how wondrous is the fresh lychee, and yet once dried, it turns sour and repellent. How is it that a thing's appearance and its flavour both change? Perhaps it is that people, too, after some years grow impure where once they were pure, coarse where once they were fine, sour where once they were sweet.\" \"Even if a little sour,\" said Baozhu, \"the finest things still surpass common flavours.\" These words drew sighs from the three young performers together. Cixian and Ziyun were rather gratified. \"We must see,\" continued Huifang, \"whether Jingyi will be the same at seventy.\" \"Spring blossom, autumn fruit — each has its season,\" laughed Cixian. \"Even the lychee in its fresh prime was worthy of the consort Yang Yuhuan. Now that it has dried, it is still worthy of Master Qu Daoweng — still superior to dates and chestnuts.\" The whole company laughed at this.",
    "\"The comparison is apt, but rather unfair to Daoweng,\" said Ziyun. \"He at least is not sour. Let him be compared to dried river scallops instead.\" \"That is even more unfair to him,\" said Cixian. \"You are a man from Zhejiang — naturally you sing the praises of river scallops. If you ask me, dried scallops are like an aging courtesan who has retired to respectable life: all the grace of her prime is gone, yet a faint smell of the old trade lingers still.\" \"Among all edible things,\" Baozhu asked Cixian, \"what would you rank first?\" \"My palate differs from most,\" said Cixian, \"and I dare not pronounce. Personally, I would put fish above all else.\" \"Well said,\" agreed Qinyan and Huifang together. \"Among foods, as among people,\" Cixian continued, \"there are distinctions: celestial rank, divine rank, transcendent rank, exquisite rank — some fit to simmer dragon and boil phoenix, others fit to drink moonlight and dine on dew. Force them into contrary roles, and neither is at its best. Hence it is that what one person praises, another disparages. Mencius says: 'In the sense of taste, all mouths are alike.'",
    "\"He was speaking in general of the seasonings blended by Yi Ya, which could suit all palates. As for today's cooks — they suit only their own palates.\" \"Exactly,\" said Ziyun. \"Take that bear's paw dish last year — what a waste it was. No wonder Duke Ling of Jin had his cook put to death. He must have had only the one paw left — had he kept back a few more pairs, his resentment might not have reached quite that pitch.\" The whole table laughed.",
    "\"Last time you were matching opera titles,\" Baozhu said to Qinyan, \"and you gave a set of four characters. Since then I thought of a couplet of my own.\" \"What is it?\" asked Qinyan. \"'Touring the Lake to Borrow an Umbrella'\" said Baozhu, \"matched with 'Searching the Mountain and Smashing the Cart.'\" \"Excellent — perfectly balanced,\" said Qinyan. \"Then there is 'Parting from Mother Under a Hail of Arrows,'\" said Huifang, \"which matches 'Admonishing the Son with a Single Sword.'\" \"In that vein,\" said Sulan, \"'Making a Ruckus in Court by Killing the Dog' matches 'Robbing the Inn and Stealing the Chicken.'\" \"They clearly know the repertoire through and through,\" laughed Ziyun, \"and recall it without the least effort.\" \"Naturally,\" said Cixian, \"— we know a few titles too, but only half by heart.\" \"I have a little diversion with dice,\" said Ziyun, \"to test your wits.\" He called for three dice. \"Is this the 'flying lyrics' game?\" asked Huifang. \"No, that is far simpler than this. You arrange three dice to form a line of poetry — whatever they suggest. For instance, a four can represent a person, or a flower, or water, or wind. It stands for whatever you imagine it to represent. Is that not easy enough? Jingyi and I shall drink, and you shall set the dice.\" Baozhu took the dice and said: \"Let me try — I may manage or I may not.\" She set a one, a four, and a five, and recited: \"'Red apricot trees lean over the clouds by the sun's edge.'\" Both Cixian and Ziyun praised it: \"Excellently done! The five is perfect for clouds — quite refined. We shall drink to that.\" Sulan snatched the dice and said: \"My turn.\" She set three red faces and recited: \"'On apricot branches, the urgency of spring calls out.'\" Ziyun praised her as well — the three red faces yielding that one word, 'urgency,' was a stroke of real inventiveness — and said to Cixian: \"We drink again.\" \"The phrase 'on the branches' seems to lack its proper ground,\" said Huifang, who then set a four and two fives, and recited: \"'A whole unbroken flush of apricot-red for ten li around.'\" \"Even better,\" said Ziyun, \"'Triumphant, the new laureate rides home swift as a flying horse' — this is a happy omen for Xiangfan. Let us all drink, Meixiang included.\" Pleased by Ziyun's apt remark, Huifang smiled warmly and drank. Qinyan took the dice, set a four and two threes, and said: \"You have all spoken of apricot blossoms — I shall speak of the peach.\" He recited: \"'Peach blossoms upon the current, gone beyond all trace.'\" \"Very good,\" said Ziyun. \"There was no restriction to apricot blossoms — anything goes.\" He and Cixian each drank. Baozhu set two threes and a one, and recited: \"'Side by side to roost, side by side to fly, through a whole lifetime.\"' Ziyun and Cixian praised her and drank. Huifang then snatched the dice back and set two sixes and a four placed at an angle. \"Look how eager he is,\" laughed Sulan, \"grabbing them from me — and now he sets out that arrangement. Surely a splendid line is coming.\" Huifang recited: \"'Beyond the pearl-screen curtain, slanting toward those within.'\" Everyone praised the line at once — \"What a perfect line, 'Beyond the pearl-screen curtain, slanting toward those within' — the dice truly look just so; let us all drink a cup together.\" Sulan set two sixes and a four and recited: \"'In each of the twelve towers, flowers are in their prime.'\" Cixian and Ziyun drank a cup apiece. Qinyan set two ones and a three and recited: \"'One by one they return to the nest — how I envy the crows.'\" Cixian glanced at Qinyan with a flicker of thought: Yunong's lines today all carried an air of desolation — why did he keep choosing such verses? Afterward the group played on in a more relaxed spirit, some placements fanciful, others not. On the whole, Huifang was judged the finest player of the afternoon.",
    "After the meal they descended and strolled for a while, crossing the little hill and the stone bridge to reach the Spring-Lingering Dell. There, over brewed tea, they fell into easy conversation. Baozhu recounted to Ziyun the matter of Qinyan's master's wife demanding the release of his indenture, together with the plans that Huifang and Sulan had proposed. \"If that is truly the case,\" said Ziyun, \"it would be very good indeed.\" He turned to Huifang and asked: \"Do you have the means to carry out this righteous act?\" \"In terms of means,\" said Huifang, \"it would be a stretch, but gathering fur from many pelts, one can still make a coat. The three of us — Yaoqing, Xiangwan, and I — could put together six hundred taels; the Wang brothers, Peixian, and Genxiang could manage four hundred.\" \"I shall contribute my share — two hundred taels,\" said Cixian, \"and Qianzhou can put in three hundred; Yong'an and Zhujun together can provide three hundred. We need not call on Genxiang, Xiangfan, or Jiantan. All told we would have one thousand eight hundred. If three thousand is the target, we are still short one thousand two hundred — which means, it goes without saying, Duxiang makes up the rest.\" \"Surely Hua Xingbei is not let off entirely without spending a single coin?\" said Ziyun. \"In my view,\" said Huifang, \"there is no need to involve him. If we go to him and demand the full sum all at once, he might agree — but then Yunong would be in his household for the rest of his life.\" Ziyun nodded. \"Quite right. But I worry that none of you is particularly flush at the moment, and if you all squeeze out these sums at once, you may find yourselves in difficulty afterward. Do not trouble yourselves at all — leave the whole of it to me. You need only go and negotiate. Once the terms are agreed, the silver is ready; they need only come to collect it. But we must act quickly: first, Yunong's leave has run out and he should not remain outside the city much longer — if he goes back in, drawing him out again would be troublesome. Go tomorrow and offer what is reasonable; everything can surely be settled.\" The three young performers all said yes. Qinyan, moved by Ziyun's generosity, was overcome with gratitude and, before he knew it, tears ran down his face. He dropped to his knees in thanks. Ziyun quickly raised him up; seeing Qinyan so overcome, he felt a pang of compassion. \"Yunong, there is no need to be so distressed,\" he said. \"I can see you were never meant for the dust of the entertainment world. It is the smallest service — not worth a word of thanks.\" The three young performers, seeing Qinyan's grief spring from genuine gratitude and Ziyun's generosity from genuine tender feeling, were themselves stirred to the core; their own tears trembled on the edge of falling. \"Who is to go and speak with her?\" asked Ziyun. \"It must be someone mature and persuasive. I fear you yourselves may not carry it off.\" \"The one indispensable person is Ye Maolin,\" said Huifang. \"He was the one who brought Yunong to the city, and he is the one who taught him to perform — and he is steady and knows how to talk.\" Qinyan nodded several times: \"Only he will do.\" \"In that case, return early,\" said Ziyun. \"This very evening, go and engage Ye Maolin. Once the matter is settled, send word to me tomorrow, and we shall see what fortune holds for Yunong. I have some business at home and cannot accompany you further.\" Ziyun left the garden with his attendants and returned to his residence.",
    "The four young performers departed in high spirits, took their leave of Cixian, and went together to find Ye Maolin and inform him of the matter. Maolin agreed at once, then said to Huifang: \"Come with me in a little while. I am old, my tongue is clumsy, and I fear I may not manage the delicate turns of speech. Please be on hand to back me up. That Madam Qing — her tongue runs like a birdsong, and I confess I find her somewhat formidable.\" \"I have heard she is a direct sort of person,\" said Huifang. \"Stroke her the right way and she will be quite easy to deal with.\" Qinyan, Baozhu, and Sulan went home ahead.",
    "Huifang and Maolin rehearsed what they would say, agreed to go together after supper, and Huifang then returned home.",
    "It happened that Tian Chunhang came to call on Huifang, and the two of them dined and talked for a while before Chunhang left. Maolin had by then been waiting outside for some time. After the first watch, Maolin took up a lantern, lit the way for Huifang, and the two arrived at the Changqing household. They did not seek out Qinyan but found Wu Mazi and asked for the widow, the wife of Changqing. Huifang saw a woman emerge who wore a white mourning kerchief and a white hemp jacket, below which she had on a long green silk skirt with white cloth bound shoes. Her face was sallow and thin, her build tall and willowy; she looked to be around thirty, with the look of someone sharp-tongued and quick-witted. Not recognising Huifang, she asked Maolin: \"And who is this?\" \"This is Master Su of the troupe,\" said Maolin. Huifang stepped forward, paid his respects, and addressed her as 'Auntie.' The widow returned the greeting, invited them to sit, and asked Ye Maolin: \"What wind has blown two of you to this chilly doorstep?\" Maolin replied cheerfully: \"We come sincerely to pay our respects to you, sister-in-law. With our Master Cao gone, you are after all a woman who does not venture far from home. If at any time you need something done outside, do send word through Old Wu Mazi — I am at leisure and quite happy to be of service.\" \"Oh, you are too kind!\" said the widow. \"Thank you for your kind thoughts. When my husband was alive, our room had at least a dozen people in it every day, gathering round that lamp, one getting up as another lay down — just like the Ministry of Personnel handing out posts, each waiting his turn. Since his death, not a single soul has crossed our threshold — not even a dog. Those two children of his are useless, and Mazi is a muddlehead who doesn't know the trade. I see this household cannot go on, and have been thinking of making other arrangements. My family is in Yangzhou; my mother is only fifty this year. My younger brother runs a second-hand clothing shop there, and I hear it is doing well. I have been thinking of going back, but I have no money in hand. When my husband was alive, money came in one hand and flew out the other. The lamp alone cost more than a thousand strings a year, to say nothing of all the other expenses and the household's upkeep. Those two foolish children cost money in food and clothing, yet how much do they earn a month? Just yesterday two strangers came for tea, and the children asked them to stay for wine and dinner. They ate and walked out. Mazi followed them, and in the end they paid only three strings. I ask you — is this any way to run a business? It makes me want to die of shame.\" \"Things are difficult all round these days,\" said Ye Maolin. \"It is not as it used to be — everyone is calculating carefully now. Look at any respectable establishment in the evening: seats full, drinkers few. The idea you mentioned about returning south is a fine one. After all, a woman living alone in the capital, with few relatives and few friends, will find it genuinely hard to keep a household going. Better to take a few thousand taels and go into a large business with your brother — a much wiser course.\" \"Oh, easy for you to say!\" laughed the widow. \"If I had a few thousand taels, I wouldn't be anxious. It is precisely because my hands are empty that I am in this difficulty. The other day I discussed it with Qinyan — I told him I would be depending on him, and asked him to go to Young Master Hua and arrange for a monthly payment of two hundred strings. He said he could not, and dared not raise it himself. I told him: if you cannot bring money back, do you expect to leave me dangling in the autumn wind? Besides, the young master has not spent much on him. I said: why not ask someone to make the case to him — get three or five thousand taels to buy out his indenture, and from then on do whatever you like. With that lump sum I could manage my old age, and naturally I would not ask him for support year after year. But he was evasive about that too, with no clear word either way.\" \"Auntie,\" said Huifang, \"so you do truly want to release him from his indenture? As it happens there is someone who has taken an interest. We came precisely to discuss this matter with you.\" \"What sort of person is he, and what office does he hold?\" asked the widow. Huifang improvised: \"He is a district magistrate from the south of the Yangtze. He is a very good sort — simply not a man of great means. He saw Qinyan the other day, praised him highly, and wishes to take him as a son, which is why he is willing to pay for his release.",
    "\"He discussed it with us yesterday. If three or five thousand taels were needed, he could not manage it — three thousand strings might perhaps be possible.\" \"Three thousand strings, and you want to release him!\" The widow exclaimed several times in astonishment. \"Do you realise that when Qinyan was performing last year, he earned a clear ten thousand strings in half a year alone? This person pays three thousand strings and gets Qinyan for his own, and then in a few months he will have recouped his investment. Dear me, dear me! If it were this easy a bargain, I would go into the business myself.\" \"Sister-in-law, that is not quite how it works,\" said Maolin. \"Consider: if he were still performing, yes, he might earn that much. But if he is taken as a son — for study, for schooling, for a proper marriage — there is nothing but spending and no earning at all. Besides, this gentleman is a kind-hearted man; helping Qinyan is in itself a good deed.\" \"I don't care about any of that,\" said the widow. \"So long as the person is willing to spend the money and meet my figure, I will let him come and arrange the release.\" \"Auntie,\" said Huifang, \"what is your actual figure? Name a definite sum, so that I may go and negotiate — whether they can meet it or not, we can speak again...\" \"Plain and simple,\" said the widow: \"three thousand taels of good silver, nothing less, and I will agree. Can he manage it or not? If he cannot, I will wait for Young Master Hua. He has a reputation as a free spender — ten thousand or eight thousand might not be beyond him. Or there is still Lord Xu — he is fond of Qinyan, and would be easier to approach. I am in no hurry!\" \"Auntie, you have heard of Young Master Hua's reputation,\" Huifang said with a cool smile, \"and three or five thousand taels is nothing to him, to be sure. But Young Master Hua has not been particularly pleased with Qinyan of late. Not only is he unlikely to buy out the indenture — he may well send him away entirely. How would Auntie know the inner workings from outside? We visit the household regularly. Now a single spare room has been allotted to him, and they don't often find uses for him. At New Year when we went to pay our respects, the young master gave each of us a silver ingot — yet Qinyan received nothing. One day I happened to see what was in his box — a mere sixty-odd taels of silver all told, accumulated from last year's Mid-Autumn Festival right to the present. As for Lord Xu, he has cooled somewhat from before, and besides, Qinyan has always kept a certain reserve with Lord Xu. If Lord Xu had truly been willing to release him, he would have done so long ago, not waited until now. Apart from these two, consider: two hundred strings a month — or three thousand taels for a full release — which is truly possible? Auntie is a sensible woman. Has more than a month at home not been enough to see through his situation? This opportunity has presented itself; we have come to speak for him, and perhaps you might add a little yourself. Auntie, see it clearly: treat him as you would your own child, and come down a little. Between the two sides we can make it work. Three thousand strings is indeed too little — but two thousand silver taels I can guarantee.\" \"Since you have come to speak,\" said the widow, \"you should be looking after my interests too — but not to the point of making your respected performer lose face. Very well then. Let us cut to the chase. I am a woman who binds her hair and wraps her feet, yet I dislike all this haggling and dragging on. I will come down two hundred taels. Two thousand eight hundred is the absolute minimum.\" Maolin, sensing the wind shifting, said to Huifang: \"Let us put it this way: go and tell that gentleman to consider it as an act of charity to a widow and orphan — a store of virtue and merit — and ask him to put up two thousand four hundred taels. We as middlemen will charge not a single cash in commission; every bit goes to the principal sum. Sister-in-law, you need not hold firm any longer. Speed is of the essence in this matter. If it is settled in a day or two, sister-in-law too can put her mind at rest. Qinyan is a straightforward person who cannot manage roundabout dealings.\" The widow weighed the matter inwardly: \"If the Hua household sends him away, and the boy is stubborn and refuses to perform again, that too will not do. As for Lord Xu, his heart is already divided among many. Better to accept the offer. Two thousand four hundred taels — six thousand strings — is not a small sum.\"",
    "Her mind was made up, though her mouth still pressed for more. But Ye Maolin, that old head, was as a soft rope — sweet words of 'sister-in-law' this, and 'sister-in-law' that — and worked the widow like a headstrong mule until she was bound fast and could only consent. \"I have committed to this,\" said Huifang, \"yet I do not know whether the other party can truly manage it. If in the end they fall short, I will have put auntie to all this trouble for nothing.\" \"You are losing your nerve,\" laughed Maolin. \"Even if they come up a thousand eight hundred short, your own connections can fill the gap — a small matter for you. And he is not likely to leave you unrewarded for it.\" \"That is the only course,\" said Huifang. \"We shall see what fate decides.\" They agreed that a reply would come the following morning after breakfast; if the matter succeeded, the silver would be sent over at once, and a written receipt would be drawn up on this side. The whole negotiation had stretched to the third watch. Huifang then took his leave of the widow and withdrew with Maolin. The widow retired within; she thought to herself: \"That young Mr. Su — a clever little rascal! Starting from three thousand strings and working up to two thousand four hundred taels — if I had softened even a little, I would have been completely outmanoeuvred. How infuriating!\" Muttering to herself, she went to sleep. Huifang and Maolin went to Qinyan's room and told him the terms that had been agreed. Qinyan was overjoyed, needing only to wait until the morrow to fly free of his cage. Huifang and Maolin then took their leave.",
    "Early the next morning, Huifang went to Yiyuan. Ziyun had not yet arrived. He waited at Cixian's rooms, and after two rounds of messengers had been sent, Ziyun came over. The matter was explained to him. Ziyun was very pleased, and summoned his chief steward, instructing him to go and draw a bank draft for two thousand four hundred taels, together with a separate draft for fifty taels as a gift for Maolin. Huifang wasted no time: he hurried back, ate quickly, found Maolin, and sent him the fifty taels first — Maolin was deeply grateful. They then went together to the widow's home. \"With great effort,\" said Huifang, \"I managed to gather one thousand nine hundred taels, and borrowed five hundred on his behalf; the whole has been made into a single draft — please accept it.\" Maolin drew up a written receipt for Qinyan to keep. Seeing the matter concluded, the widow set out a few dishes and invited Maolin and Huifang to take a light meal, asking Qinyan to sit with them. \"I have already eaten,\" said Huifang. \"Please do not trouble yourself — Master Ye, I leave you to dine alone.\" He then turned to Qinyan: \"Go and gather your things, take your leave of your shifu's spirit, thank your master's wife for her care, and come with me to the other side. Then we shall go into the city together to thank Young Master Hua — there is no time to lose.\" Qinyan did as instructed. His things were few; he called someone to help his young attendant pack and bind them. Huifang sent them all back ahead in a carrying-load, and took out a draft for ten strings as a parting gift on Qinyan's behalf to the household's servants. Qinyan dressed and donned his hat, and knelt before his shifu's spirit-tablet. He wept for a while, genuinely moved. He then made his farewell to the widow with a formal bow. The widow herself wept a good deal, and added a few words of instruction. Maolin, seeing the scene, had no heart for the wine remaining in his cup, and walked out with them. The widow accompanied them all the way to the gate; Qinyan departed with tears, and returned with Huifang to his lodgings.",
    "The following day the widow thanked Maolin with a gift of a hundred strings. Maolin had not been expecting it, and was well satisfied. But Qinyan's fate was riddled with afflictions: though he had now been released, a fresh source of trouble was about to arise. What came next, the following chapter shall reveal."
  ],
  44: [
    "Now, on the very day Qinyan was released from his indenture, Young Master Hua was hosting a flower-viewing gathering. The next morning Young Master Hua ordered Shanzhi to send someone to summon Qinyan back to the household. Shanzhi dispatched an outer attendant named Yao Xian, who set out early for the city gate. Arriving at the Changqing lodgings, he found Wu Mazi and delivered word that the leave period had expired and Qinyan was to return to the city.",
    "\"Qinyan?\" said Wu Mazi. \"Yesterday someone arranged his release from indenture. He has already moved out and is unlikely to return to the city.\" Yao Xian was startled. \"What does that mean? How could someone in our household be simply let go without permission? Where has he moved to?\" \"I don't know,\" said Mazi. \"I only heard that the one who secured his release was a man from the south of the Yangtze — he has probably moved into that man's home.\" \"Preposterous! Even if you wanted to arrange a release, you should have reported it to our young master. Our young master will never stand for this. If he finds out, there will be serious consequences.\" \"It is none of my affair,\" said Mazi. \"This was the mistress's decision — who could stop her?\" \"Where is he now, exactly?\" said Yao Xian. \"I need to find him and get a straight answer.\" \"I truly don't know his whereabouts. I only heard it said that he still intends to enter the city — he has things there he can't abandon, so naturally he will have to come back. \" Mazi's account was muddled and inconclusive, and left Yao Xian frantic. He also asked: \"Where is your mistress? I should like to question her in person.\" \"She is not in,\" said Mazi. \"She went to tend a grave at daybreak.\" Having no other option, Yao Xian left and wandered to the entrance of a theatre, pausing to look about idly. Suddenly he heard the rumble of carriage wheels behind him, bearing straight down on him. He stepped aside; looking up, he saw what appeared to be two young performers in the carriage, and the one in the back looked rather like Qinyan. By the time he thought to hurry after it for a closer look, the carriage was already far away. \"So that's it,\" thought Yao Xian. \"There he is, out in the world enjoying himself — he must have gone off to attend some wine party.\" He walked on, still thinking, when ahead of him two acquaintances appeared: one was twenty-nine-year-old Meng Qi, a household man of Xu Ziyun's; the other was thirty-nine-year-old Hu Ba, a household man of Xi the Eleventh's. Both were natives of the capital. Hu Ba was Yao Xian's first cousin on the maternal side; all three were on friendly terms. That day Hu Ba, whose master was ill and had no errands, had come out to find Meng Qi to watch a performance, and then intended to dine at a restaurant. Running into Yao Xian — who had come out from the city — Hu Ba pulled him by the arm; they exchanged greetings and retired to a restaurant, where they ordered several dishes and two pots of wine, and settled in for a leisurely chat. Meng Qi asked why Yao Xian happened to be out strolling; Yao Xian said: \"Strolling? I have a specific duty to perform and cannot be far from my post even when there is nothing to do. Today the young master sent me to fetch Qinyan — his leave has expired and he is to come back. But now I cannot find him anywhere.\" Meng Qi, hearing this, gave a start and said: \"You still intend to call him back to the household?\" \"Precisely. I went to his shifu's home just now and ran into a fellow called Mazi, who gave me a muddled account. He said that yesterday a man from the Yangtze south had arranged Qinyan's release from indenture and taken him away.",
    "\"As I see it, Qinyan is currently in our household — how could an outsider simply arrange his release and take him away? That is extraordinary news. And given how generously our young master has treated Qinyan — paying his shifu two hundred silver a month, on top of extra gifts — who in the household, besides Lin Shanzhi, enjoys a better position than he did? And yet he shows not a shred of gratitude, makes no farewell, and just walks off with someone else. I tell you, there are truly people in this world devoid of all conscience. When I report back to our young master, he will certainly have Qinyan brought back — it will come down to whether Qinyan is lucky or not.\" Meng Qi heard all this and laughed. \"Where did you hear such a thing? Qinyan is right here, perfectly well — when has he left the capital with any southerner? This is all rumour and not to be believed.\" \"It is not rumour,\" said Yao Xian. \"His own household told me.\" \"Never mind that,\" said Meng Qi. \"Have a cup of wine, and I'll tell you: ever since Qinyan's shifu died and he came out on leave, he has spent every day at our master's garden. Our master has been hosting banquets for him these past two weeks and more. As for the matter of releasing his indenture — I don't know whether Qinyan asked our master, or whether our master offered of his own accord. Yesterday our chief steward sent me to the Rixin Bank to draw a draft for two thousand four hundred taels and another for fifty taels, which was handed to Su Huifang to arrange the release on Qinyan's behalf. Just now, on the road, we saw Qinyan and Huifang sitting together in the same carriage, on their way back to our master's garden. From the look of things, our master intends to keep him close.",
    "\"We assumed he was no longer in your household, and so our master stepped in to take care of him. Had we known he was still in your household, our master is on such good terms with your young master — they are always exchanging fine antiques and valuable objects as gifts. If he wanted this person, he had only to send a note to your young master — surely your young master would have given him up? Why spend two thousand four hundred taels? What a needless waste.\" \"So that is the story,\" said Yao Xian. \"Even so, even if your master wanted him, he should have informed our young master first — Qinyan has not yet formally left the household. Not to put too fine a point on it, your master was a little rash.\"",
    "Hu Ba then put in: \"I have never seen this Qinyan — I don't know what he looks like. As for our master, last month at the Hongjisi Temple, at the gathering hosted by Master Wei, Qinyan attended our master for a whole day, and our master gave him a pair of emerald bracelets that had belonged to his consort. Those bracelets were purchased in Guangdong for one thousand four hundred silver coins; in the capital they would be worth even more. Now our master has taken ill, and Qinyan has not come to inquire after him even once. This person seems to have no conscience at all. He was with your young master and now wants to be with our master — clearly a man of no constancy. Who knows where he will land next?\" The two of them, ignorant of the true state of affairs, rattled on with talk that was plausible enough on the surface yet wide of the mark.",
    "Yao Xian finished his meal, offered his thanks, and returned to the city, where he reported to Shanzhi. He relayed Qinyan's recent doings — first as Mazi had told them, then as Meng Qi and Hu Ba had reported — without leaving out a single word, and with his tongue loosened, he added a good many embellishments of his own. He also said that on the road he had seen Qinyan sharing a carriage with another young performer, apparently going off to attend some wine party. Shanzhi listened, fell quiet for a moment, and then said: \"What is all this? Is it true or false? If I pass it on to our master exactly as you have told it, and there is any false element, things will go very badly.\"",
    "\"How would I dare to tell lies?\" said Yao Xian. \"These are words spoken by Meng Qi of Lord Xu's household and Hu Ba of the Xi family's household — with witnesses to what was said. Would I dare add a word? Is it something to jest about?\" Shanzhi turned it over in her mind: \"How could Qinyan be so ungrateful? Not only has the young master loved him for nothing — I have taken care of him for nothing as well.\" Then the thought shifted: \"Looking at his heart, he has always been reluctant to be here, always pining after some young Master Mei. Naturally he is happier out there. To be at Lord Xu's is one thing. But how could he also attend wine parties for Wei Pincai and Xi the Eleventh? Has he no self-respect, or does he care nothing for the young master's face? The jade bracelets are not worth all that much, and yet he could sink so low. And here in the household he always put on such airs — the manner of a superior being, a cold hauteur about him. So that is the reality of it, now plain to see. At this point I can no longer help conceal things for you — better to tell the truth outright. A person of true character acting out of true principle — perhaps it will shame someone too. His manner is refined and doesn't look like a performer's; there seems to be not a trace of vulgarity in him. Yet now, it turns out — it is those with a trace of vulgarity who do not dare to take unauthorized leave, while this one makes a spectacle of himself. Shall I just tell it straight?\" Her mind made up, she walked to the outer study and called softly to little Xiang'er through the whitewashed wall. She heard Xiang'er's silvery laughter from within, and only after several calls did the girl emerge. \"What is it?\" Xiang'er asked. \"I need to report something.\" \"The young master has gone to the garden,\" said Xiang'er. \"Did the young master go alone, or with the mistress?\" \"The young master went from here accompanied by Sister Bao, Sister Zhen, and Sister Rui to the garden, to see the peach blossoms again. The mistress did not go.\" Then Shanzhi heard a voice inside the room: \"Listen — who is that?\" The voice replied: \"Lin Shanzhi, of course — who else?\" Shanzhi recognized it as Huazhu and Hezhu, and went off quickly toward the garden. She passed through a blaze of crimson and pink, in a languid and gentle breeze, and went straight along to the Liu Xian Courtyard. Reaching the rear of the garden, she could hear laughter everywhere, and what sounded like verse recitation — in girls' voices. Shanzhi lightened her step and circled to the western side, concealing herself behind a Taihu rock, peering through a gap in the stone from a distance. She saw Rui Zhu, dressed in a peach-pink silk jacket and green silk vest, kneeling under the peach trees and reciting the \"Song of Everlasting Regret.\" She had arrived at the lines:",
    "\"She grasps her gown and pushes back the pillow, rises and wanders restless through the night; / Pearl blinds and silver screens roll open one by one in slowly shifting light.\"\n\n\"Her cloud-piled hair is half-undone from sleep just ended; / She descends the hall with her headdress and her garments not yet mended.\"\n\n\"The wind sweeps her immortal robes, billowing and lifting high, / As if she danced again the 'Rainbow Skirt and Feathered Robe.\"'\n\n\"Her jade face in its solitude, tears crossed upon the sill — / A spray of pear blossoms in spring rain, trailing its tears still.\"\n\nAt the line \"a spray of pear blossoms in spring rain,\" Rui Zhu stumbled, repeated two lines, and could not go on. The young master burst out laughing: \"Still kneeling, and you still can't recite it — you deserve to be struck.\" Rui Zhu's face had turned deep red; she tried and tried again but could not recall the words. Beside her, Ai Zhu was laughing at her; behind the young master, Bao Zhu was scratching her own cheek in mock shame. The teasing drove Rui Zhu nearly to tears. These past two days the young master and the mistress had devised an entertainment for the ten Pearl-maids: teaching them Tang poems, making them recite the poems from memory once learned, and imposing penalties for errors.",
    "For many mistakes, a kneeling penalty could be followed by a rapping of the palms. Today Bao Zhu had recited the six \"Untitled\" poems of Li Yishan, with only one wrong character and no demerit recorded. Ai Zhu had recited the \"Song of the Pipa\" without a single error. Rui Zhu, reciting the \"Song of Everlasting Regret,\" had already accumulated many errors, and so was kneeling on the ground; now she could not recite further, while the other three Pearl-maids chipped in with a word or a phrase to tease her. Half beside herself with vexation, she did not dare simply stand up and walk away.",
    "Young Master Hua was enjoying the scene thoroughly when he suddenly noticed that through the aperture of the Taihu rock something seemed to be spying on them. He called out: \"Who is behind the Taihu rock?\" Shanzhi gave a start and quickly stepped forward, standing with hands at her sides. \"Why did you come and then not come forward — what were you doing hiding behind the rock?\" said the young master. \"I arrived just now,\" said Shanzhi, \"and hearing the young master in conversation, I paused to glance from behind the Taihu rock before coming forward.\" \"What is it?\" said the young master. \"You sent Yao Xian early this morning to summon Qinyan; Yao Xian has returned,\" said Shanzhi. \"And Qinyan?\" \"Qinyan did not come back.\" \"Why has Qinyan still not come back? Has something detained him?\" \"I fear Qinyan will not be able to come.\" The young master was startled. \"What do you mean — is Qinyan ill?\" \"No.\" \"If there is nothing wrong, why can he not come?\" Shanzhi made a show of hesitation. The young master grew deeply suspicious and urged her: \"Just tell me exactly what Yao Xian reported — don't be evasive.\" \"I fear the young master will be angry when I tell him.\" This made the young master still more uneasy; he pressed her again, and Shanzhi then recounted in full what Yao Xian had told her.",
    "The four Pearl-maid attendants, hearing all this, were also astonished. And Rui Zhu, still kneeling on the ground, had been staring blankly at Shanzhi as she spoke, lost in a dream of her own: a shower of petals had fallen all over her head, and she was idly chewing a petal in her mouth, which she then spat out onto Ai Zhu's hand. Ai Zhu gave her a look.",
    "Hearing all this, Young Master Hua was overcome with fury; the colour drained from his face. He kept saying: \"Can this be true! Outrageous! Outrageous! Qinyan has utterly lost all human conscience — the like of it is rarely seen. And Duxiang — smiling on the outside, a blade within — he has gone too far in insulting me. Do you think I will simply let this pass? Go at once and send Yao Xian back — he must bring Qinyan here, no matter what. I must question him face to face and hear his reasons. I care nothing for this Xu Duxiang — I intend to have a reckoning with him and see who is in the right. Is there such an outrage as this in the world? If we were strangers, that would be one thing; but as intimate friends, he had no right to set out to deceive me. Why did he not arrange this release earlier? He waited until I had Qinyan here with me, and then made a show of his private resources and arranged the release. Qinyan himself is truly detestable. In what particular was he treated poorly? And yet his heart was always with that other quarter!\" Shanzhi gently soothed him: \"Young master, please calm your anger. Qinyan came to the capital only recently, and his shifu was the sort who let him have his own way and spoiled him. He spent half a year here, and I can say not only was he not badly treated — he could travel the whole world and not find a finer situation. One cannot understand why he was always knitting his brows and shedding tears behind closed doors. He has his own inner sorrow that he cannot put into words. Such a faithless person — why should the young master keep him in mind? In my view, one need not be angry: watch — he will not stay long at Lord Xu's either. Lord Xu's garden has eight or ten people about every day; if Qinyan is treated the same as all the others, he will certainly be uncomfortable. There is no turning a wild pheasant into a barnyard hen. His conscience ruined, what good can come of it? Heaven itself may not permit it. Besides, this Xi the Eleventh — I do not know him personally, but he is said to be a thoroughly disreputable man. To attend wine parties for such a one — is that not a disgrace? In my view, that single vulgarity alone, even setting aside the matter of Lord Xu, is enough reason not to want him.\" The young master, hearing Shanzhi's words, felt his anger subside a little.",
    "Shanzhi then caught Bao Zhu's eye, and Bao Zhu also sought to console him: \"Shanzhi speaks rightly. If Qinyan's heart had truly been with the young master, then even if someone had arranged his release, he would not have concealed it but would have come to inform the young master in person. If he had come to inform the young master, would the young master not have been willing to release him? This person is both confused and faithless — what use is such a one? Besides, last year it was he who chose to come; this year it is he who chooses to leave. The young master's kindness to him — who in the world does not know it? This is his own ill fortune — he is not able to receive such a blessing. If the young master were determined to have him brought back, he would certainly not dare disobey; but that would make it seem as though one cannot do without him, and he would think himself all the more valuable. In our humble opinion, from now on let him come if he will and stay away if he will — the household loses nothing by his absence. As for Lord Xu, he was certainly wrong; but we counsel the young master not to press the matter with him. Over one person of no great consequence, to damage the friendship of two generations of families is not worth it. And people will naturally say Lord Xu was in the wrong — poaching another's favourite — while praising the young master's magnanimity.\"",
    "These two between them had coaxed the young master considerably; his anger had partly subsided, but he could not entirely release it. He sat in silence.",
    "Rui Zhu had been kneeling all this time — though a cushion had been placed beneath her — and her knees had grown quite painful. Nature was also pressing her with some urgency; her face flushed crimson in that expression somewhere between the desire to laugh and the desire to cry, which was rather pitiable.",
    "The young master had worked himself up into a rage and then been calmed by Shanzhi's and Bao Zhu's words, and had quite forgotten that Rui Zhu was still kneeling.",
    "In desperation Rui Zhu finally said: \"I could kneel until tomorrow and still not remember it. You had better just give me my punishment.\" The young master laughed in spite of himself. \"Get up,\" he said. \"I had forgotten you were still kneeling.\" Rui Zhu stood, bent over, rubbed her knees, and sauntered off saying: \"What bad luck — kneeling all that time for nothing.\" She went off to find a secluded corner to relieve herself. Young Master Hua rose and went to the mistress's quarters; Bao Zhu and Ai Zhu followed him in. Zhen Zhu waited for Rui Zhu, and the two walked together. Shanzhi slowly escorted the young master out of the garden, and was just turning to leave when a handful of petals was thrown over her head. She spun around to see Rui Zhu and Zhen Zhu scolding her: \"Someone was kneeling right there, and you were spying through that stone-hole! A pox on your eyes!\" \"And you'll be getting your hands slapped again tomorrow,\" said Shanzhi, and walked away.",
    "The young master returned to his rooms, and seeing the mistress, he tried not to broach the subject — but could not hold it back, and told her of Ziyun's arrangement of Qinyan's release from indenture. \"What does 'release from indenture' mean?\" asked Madam Hua. \"In the old days his shifu paid to have him, so all earnings went to the shifu,\" the young master explained. \"With his release, he is no longer considered the shifu's person and may act for himself. Yesterday Duxiang spent two thousand four hundred taels to release Qinyan's indenture.\" \"So Qinyan now belongs to Duxiang,\" said the mistress. \"Precisely. I am truly furious — Duxiang shows contempt for everyone, and never even told me. I intend to pay him a personal visit tomorrow, and I want to send Qinyan out of the capital entirely and forbid him from remaining in the city.\" The mistress smiled: \"Is this worth getting upset over? If someone else chose to release his indenture, what concern is that of ours? After all, Qinyan cannot really be counted as one of our household members. If he does not wish to remain here, let him go.",
    "\"Duxiang's lord and our lord were the closest of friends — why damage a friendship of generations over Qinyan? My advice is that you need not act on this at all. When all is said and done, Qinyan is a performer — if this becomes a quarrel, both families will earn an unpleasant reputation for keeping company with such people.\" The young master, who had always held his wife in great esteem, heard her speak with calm and reason, and felt more than half his anger dissipate. He murmured: \"You are right.\" Yet he could not quite let Qinyan go from his heart. He went back and forth in his mind — unable to act, unable to desist — and drifted through the day in a mood of empty restlessness. The mistress soothed him further. The young master could only try to put the matter aside for the time being. Through the night his grievance lay unresolved, and the next morning it flared up again without warning. He ordered Shanzhi to have Qinyan's clothing-chests and belongings loaded into a cart, wrote a letter, and directed Shanzhi to deliver it in person to Yiyuan and hand it directly to Duxiang, to see what he would make of it. Shanzhi had no choice but to carry out the command.",
    "This was the second day after Qinyan's release. Qinyan had originally intended to return to the Hua household that day, but Ziyun was planning a banquet on the sixth day of the month — to send off Nanxiang and Chunhang, and to host Master Qu Daosheng, with Ziyu, Zhongqing, and others invited to keep them company. As today was only the fourth, they resolved to wait until the seventh for Qinyan to go back, and to draft a note to Young Master Hua explaining that after his leave expired, Qinyan had felt unwell and had been kept a few days for some fresh air. So Qinyan was quite at ease and enjoyed these extra days of leisure.",
    "That day Huifang had gone out, and Qinyan came to Yiyuan on his own. The pear blossoms were now in bloom; Ziyun and Cixian were chatting with Baozhu in the Pear Blossom Courtyard when Qinyan arrived and greeted them. \"Yunong,\" laughed Cixian, \"now that you are your own master, why not resign from the Hua household and come to live here?\" \"I would truly like nothing better,\" said Qinyan with a laugh. \"But how would one go about resigning?\" \"Heaven forbid!\" laughed Ziyun. \"Hua Xingbei would say I had stolen his favourite — that lawsuit might never be settled. Watch out it does not end up in an imperial complaint. By the seventh day you can go back. When did you leave in the first place?\" \"The twenty-seventh of the first month,\" said Qinyan. \"So it has been forty days already — how time flies!\" said Ziyun. \"When I was at the household, the days seemed to crawl,\" said Qinyan, \"and out here they seem to race.\" Ziyun said to Cixian: \"These past two days both Zhujun and Xiangfan have been cramming for the examinations. It is understandable for Xiangfan — he wants to make a name for himself under Meixiang's admiring eye. As for Zhujun, the fact that he can sit still long enough to write and compose shows how keen his ambition is — which is something no man can entirely escape.\" \"This year there are two paths open,\" said Cixian. \"If one fails the metropolitan examination, one can still sit for the Erudite Scholars examination. Passing the Erudite Scholars examination — is that not finer in its way than passing as a jinshi?\" \"Far harder to pass, actually,\" said Ziyun. \"A good birth by that route is not something I can hope for. Hoping to pass as a jinshi is not entirely unreasonable, but then I have gone and filled a vacancy, which takes the wind out of one's sails — this year I can only watch others compete. Of the two, Zhujun and Xiangfan, who do you think has the better chance?\"",
    "\"Their abilities are about evenly matched,\" said Cixian. \"Xiangfan's style is exceptionally polished and in the right vein; Zhujun's gifts are more wide-ranging and bold. If they meet with an examiner who is conservative, he will likely be undervalued. In palace examination composition, Zhujun falls short of Xiangfan; but in the Erudite Scholars examination, Zhujun would have the advantage. My view is that Genxiang is certain to pass this year, and Jiantan and Zhuoran each have a nine-in-ten chance.\" \"And you yourself,\" said Ziyun, \"are a foregone conclusion.\" \"I am not entering,\" said Cixian. \"I know my own lack of fortune in such things.\" \"What sort of talk is that?\" said Ziyun. \"If you choose not to sit for the regular examinations, that is one thing — one might at least say you have no interest in advancement. But this Erudite Scholars examination is meant to identify the finest talent in the realm; even the most eminent elders who have retired to private life still come to sit for it. Could a man of your complete gifts truly not participate? I will commission someone to submit your name by force — you will have no choice but to go.\" Cixian smiled but said nothing. \"If one passes,\" asked Baozhu, \"what office does one hold?\" \"Compiler in the Hanlin Academy,\" said Ziyun. \"Can Genxiang take the examination?\" asked Qinyan. \"He is only a xiucai.\" \"He can,\" said Ziyun. \"You yourself will surely go,\" said Qinyan. \"Active officials are not permitted to sit,\" said Ziyun. \"I have already taken up a post. And as for Qianzhou — I fear he cannot enter either; he will likely receive his assignment sometime around the fifth month.\"",
    "While they were talking, the gatekeeper came in to announce: \"Young Master Hua has sent someone who wishes to see the master in person, and has also brought several trunks.\" Ziyun was puzzled. \"What trunks? Have the visitor come in.\" Before the words were out, Shanzhi had already walked into the Pear Blossom Courtyard. Qinyan caught sight of Shanzhi and immediately retreated behind the house to listen in concealment, wondering what business had brought him. Shanzhi greeted Ziyun and Cixian formally, and said: \"The young master sends his respects to both gentlemen, and asks me to deliver this letter.\" He offered it with both hands. Ziyun took it; on the envelope he read: \"Four leather trunks, to be delivered to and receipted by Second Lord Xu.\" He acknowledged greetings to Young Master Hua, opened the letter, and Cixian read it together with him. It read:",
    "\"On the twenty-seventh day of the first month, my household page Qinyan, following the death of his shifu Changqing, was granted one month's leave to manage the funeral arrangements. As this leave has now been exceeded by several days, I sent my man Yao Xian to the city outskirts yesterday to summon him back, and only then learned that my elder brother had arranged Qinyan's release from indenture and has already received him into his household. I therefore send his chests and belongings herewith, requesting that you kindly receive and forward them; I presume Qinyan is in no position to come and collect them himself. I have however heard that this young man has conducted himself in a very base manner, having attended wine parties at various establishments indiscriminately, caring for nothing but advantage. I was enraged to hear it. I had considered recalling and severely disciplining him, but feared this would be contrary to my elder brother's wishes. Nevertheless, I trust that in future you will keep him under strict oversight and prevent him from repeating his former transgressions. My elder brother's broad-minded generosity is beyond dispute, yet I for my part shall remain vigilant, and should I have occasion to hear further reports, I shall relay them in full so that you may act on my behalf and expel this person — so that your noble garden may not be brought into disrepute. In haste, this brief note, with wishes for your continued wellbeing.\"\n\nZiyun read through the letter and did not know where to begin: the injustice was total, the wrong impossible to argue away. His hands turned cold with anger. He and Cixian looked at each other in silence, and exchanged a few cold laughs. Cixian asked Shanzhi: \"What did your young master say to you?\" \"Nothing in particular,\" said Shanzhi. \"He only asked me to deliver Qinyan's trunks clearly to his lordship and to ask whether there was any reply.\" Ziyun was too angry to speak. Cixian said: \"Strange — how did all this come about? There is no time to write a reply at this moment; tomorrow I will come with Lord Xu and speak to your young master face to face.\" Shanzhi replied with a \"Yes,\" withdrew, had the trunks brought and left with the gatekeeper, and departed without further ceremony.",
    "On this side, Qinyan still did not know the reason for the visit, but had gathered that the trunks had been brought. When he heard Shanzhi leave, he quickly came out. He found Ziyun pale and leaning back in his chair; Baozhu and Cixian were still reading the letter. Qinyan came forward to look; Cixian was inclined to conceal it, but Ziyun said: \"Let him see — where does all this come from? Hua Xingbei truly behaves not like a decent person — listening to someone's slanders and thus abusing people. Outrageous! Outrageous!\" Qinyan had been managing well enough before he looked at the letter — but reading it word by word, a surge of fury rose within him; a darkness swept across his eyes, something seemed to lodge in his throat blocking all breath, his eyes rolled back, and he fell backward. Ziyun, Cixian, and Baozhu were all struck dumb with fright, and rushed to support him. Ziyun pressed hard on the philtrum; Cixian with one hand supported his back and with the other massaged his chest; a rattling sound came from Qinyan's throat. Cixian lifted him and propped him sitting against his own body. After the time it takes to drink a cup of tea, Qinyan's head gave a slight nod, then he bent forward and expectorated a clot of phlegm, then retched up a great quantity more. \"He is better, he is better,\" said Baozhu, patting him on the back. Qinyan gradually began to revive. When he opened his eyes, tears poured forth like a spring. Ziyun and the others, watching him, were stricken with grief; Baozhu's own tears fell without cease. They helped him to the couch in the side room and propped a pillow behind him. \"Do not grieve,\" said Ziyun. \"Tomorrow I will take you with me, and we will make this right — all will be clear.\" Qinyan suddenly burst out sobbing — a wail of grief that held the injustice of three years' rainless drought, the cruelty of midsummer frost.",
    "Ziyun and the others felt their own hearts wrung within them; the three could find not a single word of consolation. He wept for a full hour, until at last there were tears but no sound, and he wept on in silent, desolate grief.",
    "Seeing Qinyan in this state, Ziyun was deeply moved. He thought to himself: \"Hua Xingbei has gone too far in insulting people without verifying anything. I had intended to go and set the record straight, but if I go to defend myself, it will only seem as though I am grovelling before him. Better to leave it. Severing this friendship altogether would be no great loss.\" He said aloud: \"Yunong, stop crying. Your goodness is known to all. These words — who would believe them? It must have been Lin Shanzhi who stirred things up from the inside, resulting in this — and now even I am painted with the same brush. In my view, there is no place there where you can feel at ease. Why must you depend on him? Since your trunks have been sent here, you need not go to see him again. If you were to go, you would only meet with further humiliation. Stay here for a few more days, and we will work something out.\" Qinyan was still weeping quietly; he expressed his thanks and said: \"You treat me with such grace and loyalty — I will never forget it for as long as I live. And yet for my sake you have had to bear all this anger and trouble. It is my miserable fate that has harmed so many people. I truly do not want to live. Death would be clean — it would put an end to all the anger and grief. Every day I live is a day of bitterness. I have already lived two years more than I should have. Now comes the very time when I ought to die.\" And with that he wept again. Cixian said: \"When you first entered the Hua household, I told Duxiang then that it would come to no good — and now that you have come out, it is in fact a good thing. From here on you have not a single fetter — you are free to do as you wish. You will naturally leave your old profession behind. Live here in this garden with me as a friend who forgets the difference in our years; I will teach you the qin, chess, calligraphy, painting, poetry, lyrics, and verse — everything, until you are accomplished in them all. In time you will be known as a man of refinement — is that not better than being a page in the Hua household? You should be glad of it — why grieve? Besides, that letter was written in the heat of anger, and naturally the words are ugly.\" \"Jingyi speaks rightly,\" said Ziyun. \"In fact, I intend one day to invite your whole troupe here and settle them all in the garden — none of you need perform again. In a few years I will have cultivated an exceptional circle of people — far superior to those half-educated examination candidates and those third-rate scholars.\" Then, turning to Cixian: \"A slip of the tongue — a slip of the tongue! You hold the elevated tribute scholar's rank and are well beyond the ordinary xiucai.\" \"I am still a xiucai,\" said Cixian. \"And you are a juren.\" \"A most unaccomplished one,\" said Ziyun. Wishing to lift Qinyan's spirits, Baozhu laughed and said to Cixian: \"Tribute scholar — 'tribute scholar' — our youyi performers actually rank above the tribute scholars! When we apply ourselves to study, that is truly 'learning and, when opportunity comes, excelling'; and should any of us become an official, we would be 'governing and, when opportunity comes, excelling.'\" \"This is too much!\" laughed Cixian. \"Not only are you insulting me — you have dragged Duxiang into the insult as well.\" Baozhu made a deep bow of apology: \"Forgive my thoughtless words.\" Ziyun laughed too, and Qinyan at last ceased weeping.",
    "Just then Huifang arrived. Seeing Qinyan's state, he was greatly surprised. On hearing what had happened, he clapped his hands with delight: \"There is no better fortune in the world — one could not ask for it — and you are still weeping about it?\" Cixian then relayed Ziyun's words about not letting them perform anymore and keeping them all in the garden. \"Nothing could be finer,\" said Huifang, \"though I fear our base-born fate may not allow for such leisured grace. I have been wanting to change my way of life these past two years, but there is no alternative livelihood to change to. Following officials around is no different from performing. Starting a business — I have no head for it. And here in the capital, even if one changed one's trade, people still know one's face; one would have to leave the capital entirely before a fresh start were possible. Do you suppose I enjoy performing? I am trapped inside it and cannot get out. Even if it brought in ten thousand taels a year and made me a wealthy man — what would that amount to? I can never escape the label of 'secondary role.' I am absolutely resolved to change my trade.\" \"My heart is the same as yours,\" said Baozhu. \"Only heaven knows whether heaven will grant our wish.\" That night the three performers stayed on in the garden, talking and chatting, and Qinyan's grief eased considerably. Ziyun said to Huifang: \"Yunong is not entirely at ease staying with you, and you cannot be at home to keep him company all day. Rather than that, let him come and stay here for a few days. We can think of a proper long-term plan — we must find a sound and lasting arrangement for him.\" \"My original intention was to keep him only a day or two and then send him back to the city,\" said Huifang. \"If he were to stay indefinitely, it really would not be quite right. And his situation now is not what it was before. Better to move here — there is room to breathe and distract himself. I wonder what Yunong thinks?\" Qinyan had no firm opinion of his own, and simply said: \"It would be more convenient here.\" So Baozhu and Huifang stayed on that night as well, keeping Qinyan company in the Pear Blossom Courtyard of the garden. Ziyun went back to his own quarters; Cixian also returned to his rooms. The three lay in the same bed and talked on until the fifth watch before sleeping.",
    "Meanwhile, Shanzhi returned to the Hua household. Young Master Hua asked what Duxiang had looked like when she delivered the letter to the garden. \"When I arrived,\" said Shanzhi, \"I found them all in the Pear Blossom Garden. As I entered, Qinyan and Baozhu were there — Qinyan saw me and immediately moved away. Lord Xu inquired after the young master's health, opened the letter, and read it for a moment without saying a single word, then gave a single cold laugh. Lord Xiao said there was no time to write a reply, and asked me to return and convey his respects, saying he would come in person to see the young master tomorrow. I handed the trunks over to their gatekeeper, and that was received, and I came away.\" After sending Shanzhi off, Young Master Hua thought to himself that Ziyun would certainly acknowledge himself in the wrong and personally return Qinyan — which would dissolve his resentment. But instead, not a word was spoken, and the trunks were coolly accepted; not even a written reply was offered — the sheer impudence of it, with only Xiao Cixian having the grace to say something by way of courtesy. This new affront was like Zhou Gong Jin meeting Zhuge Wuhou — his brows drew together in a heavy frown and a chill spread across his face, and he found himself without words. What came next, the following chapter shall reveal."
  ],
};
